        "text": " pointed at the Pharisees and Sadducees, to whom it was addressed no less sternly by our Lord (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 23:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It described the venomous hypocrisy which turned religion itself into a vice, and hid a deadly malice under the glittering semblance of a zeal for orthodoxy. But let it be borne in mind that only teachers of transcendent holiness, and immediately inspired by God with fervency and insight, may dare to use such language. The metaphor was one of those desert symbols which would be suggested to St John both by the scene of his preaching and by the language of Isaiah with which he shews special familiarity.",
        "children": []
      },
